hael Paterniti's "Should We Get Used To Mass Shootings?" (2016) -- t4.4 The Resilient Medium in Rachel Kaadzi Ghansah's "A Most American Terrorist" (2017) -- t4.5 The Reflexivity of Violence -- tConclusion -- tThe Possibilities of Human Media -- tBibliography0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aAs a literary genre, the nonfictional reportage has particular implications for the role of the writer. Pascal Sigg shows how six U.S. American writers, including David Foster Wallace, George Saunders, and Rachel Kaadzi Ghansah, reflect on themselves as human media in their reportage. The writers assert themselves in a postmodern way by scrutinizing their own mediation. As it also traces and develops the theorization of reportage as genre along the reporters' early concerns with technical media, this pioneering contribution to literary journalism studies paves a way for a new materialist approach in the under-researched field.  afunded by Swiss National Science Foundation (SNSF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAmerican Studies. 4aDigital Media. 4aHuman. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aMedia. 4aMediation. 4aMediatization. 4aReportage. 4aSelf-Reflection. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Studies.  aDigital Media.  aHuman.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedia.  aMediation.  aMediatization.  aReportage.  aSelf-Reflection.2 aSwiss National Science Foundation (SNSF)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839473269?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839473269zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/d